        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName> <date>24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> November 1848</date></p>
			<p>Revd and respected Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">I take the liberty of writing you this as<lb/> it is no more than my duty to let you know in what position<lb/> I am&#44; for <sic>oweing</sic> to the length of time that I have owed you<lb/> your account you must think that my principle is bad&#44; but<lb/> I trust that the following will remove any bad impression you<lb/> may have formed of me&#44; in the first place I must inform you<lb/> that had it not have been for the brutality of <persName>Mr. Joseph</persName><lb/> during his Treasurership your account would have been<lb/> paid long ere this&#44; as I have often begged a dollar of him<lb/> to go to market and have been refused although I was entitled<lb/> to 40 times the amount it is true I had no right to make use<lb/> of your money&#44; but on the other hand I only received it by <add>&#63;</add><lb/> and <add>&#63;</add>&#44; and of three or four I never received it at all. 2ndly<lb/> my salary is now very limited indeed out of which I have to pay<lb/> &#163;50 a year for two years to come for expenses incurred at my<lb/> election&#44; finta I have to pay as also income tax&#44; very heavy<lb/> Doctors bills since my family have been here&#44; and besides<lb/> my family&#44; a Mother in law and sister to maintain&#44; so that<lb/> you will see that a Salary of &#163;200 <hi rend="underline">including everything</hi><lb/>does not go very far&#44; more especially here where every thing<lb/> is so enormously expensive. I therefore most earnestly<lb/> intreat that you will grant me time to settle your account<lb/> as God knows that it grieves me to the heart that I am not able<lb/> to answer your call as my principle is good but unfortunately<lb/> not my means. I have endeavored by all the means in my power<lb/> to send you a something but find it impossible. I once more<lb/> intreat that this will not be the means of lessening our<lb/> friendship&#44; but that if in return for your kindness you think<lb/> there is anything that I can do for you here&#44; I shall not only<lb/> consider it a pleasure but a duty to serve you. Hoping<lb/> this will meet with a favorable reply&#44; and that at all</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>events you will not instruct <persName>Mr. Isel</persName> to use any harsh means&#44; and<lb/> I fervently Pray that the Guardian of Israel may spare you for<lb/> many years in health and happiness. <persName>Mrs. Piza</persName> desires to be kindly<lb/> remembered to you&#44; and hopes you will think it a liberty she has<lb/> taken in enclosing a letter for her brother&#44; as we have written<lb/> so repeatedly and received no answer that we have adopted<lb/> this plan of letting him know how we are.</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">I remain</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)">Revd. Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Your sincere friend and well wisher</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">David Pizal</persName></p>
			<p>An early answer will<lb/> greatly oblige</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><persName>Frank Williams</persName> <add>The preceding line written sideways</add></p>
			<p>Paid&#8212;</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)"><placeName>Bishopsgate St Within</placeName></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p>Minister to the Spanish and Portuguese</p>
			<p>Jewish Congregation</p>
